<P>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#FF0000">*If HTML and/or <A HREF="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/ubbcode.html" target=_blank>UBB Code</A> are enabled, this means you can use HTML and/or UBB Code in your message.</FONT>
<br>
<P><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aldur</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">From studies done, mor on non uber encounters seems to produce very little actual benefit, mok is even worse and practically produces zero.<P>Firstly lets look at what we want from each spell.<P>Mok is a spell to help people regenerate hps.  In a similar way to any regeneration spell.  It has similar disadvantages to regen spells, as in it will heal regardless of whether or not they need healing.<P>It however does not heal everyone in the party, only melee members, and it can also be resisted.  It also has to be cast on every mob, which takes up valuable time.<P>So lets look at the figures compared to the two popular group regen spells in the end game.  It is slightly lower level but I think relatively comparable.  Note that for clerics and druids, both are provided on velious bp so comparison purposes ill use the cost in mana of the spell.<P>Regrowth of the grove heals 15hps a tick for 15 mins for a total of 2250 hps.  It applies this to all party members for a total of 13500 hps healed every quarter of an hour.  It does this for 600 mana for a 22.5:1 hp to mana ratio.<P>Mark of Karn costs 125 mana so on that ratio, it would heal a total of 2812.5 hps.<P>Now I will confess to not knowing the exact break down of how mark of karn heals, whether or not the delay of the weapon is taken unslowed or slowed, but lets for the sake of arguement assign a reasonable figure of 6 hps healed ever 2 seconds, per main hand hit.<P>With this taken into account, using 2 mainhand swings per round (above average), it would heal 360 hps per minute per attacker.  Given the total duration of mok is 3.5 mins, you would have to have 2.2 tanks attacking the mob for its entire duration in order for it to rival the healing power of regrowth of the grove.<P>If this was a situation (and forgetting damage distribution - this affects regen spells just as much), it would be useful to cast it, since frankly put 22:1 healing ratio, even incredibly slowly is absolutely amazing.<P>This is not the situation however.  As you get higher the damage capabilities of players goes up, and whilst hps of mobs go up, they don't to this extent.<P>Warrior lizards for example in CT have around 15k hps. With just one high quality warrior only attacking, its quiet possible that it would die within 3.5 minutes.  And warriors have much more hps than the average critter.  Raptors for example last less than a minute, absolutely destroying the spell.<P>And this is a zone where everything is mean and difficult.<P>Translate it into a zone where its much easier and mobs easily last less than a minute and it becomes practically worthless, other than for a secondary ability to dispell damage shields, something that the spell dispell can do much better.<P>In order for it to be effective, either the healing rate of the spell has to raise considerable, scaling to the damage the critter is recieving, not the delay of the weapons, or it becomes a buff cast upon players.  If it was cast on the player and not on the mob, efficency would be much less of an issue, resists wouldn't be a problem, and it would take less of the clerics time.<P>Lets look at mor.  I'll be the first to say that mor is not nearly as bad as mok in usefulness, in solo tanking situations it is very useful, but in groups it is practically worthless.  Calculation of damage put it that in order for it to stack against judgement, the critter must hit someone 21.5 times.  <P>Firstly, resist rates of mor are relatively high.  Judgement rarely ever gets resisted, its a shock if it happens, i am used to seeing it always hit for 925 (unfocused, and lets not even get into focus items affecting effecency).  Secondly agro.  In order for mor to be efficent, I have to throw it early, otherwise it makes it even less useful.  This either causes agro, and potencial healing, or the inability to sit for a few ticks which reduces efficency even more.  Judgement however can be cast anytime after the tank has established agro and you can sit immediately after.<P>The mob also has to hit the tank.  Again the life span of said mob is in question, the quicker it is killed, the less it will hit the tank.  Combine slow, quick kill rate and a good tank who rarely gets hit and it has been shown even in small 3 man groups, not to be efficent.<P>What to do?<P>Personelly, I think a vast majority of the clerics lack of damage adding capability can be solved with fixing this single simple spell.  Rather than fix it so that it was in line with our nukes, it should be made much more powerful (but not too powerful), so that when in a group where healing is less useful, it is the spell to cast.<P>What would be good, is rather than giving a reverse damage shield, is if it caused a damage amplify on the said mob.<P>If it amplified damage by a mere 10%, lets look at some numbers.  On a mob with 10k hps it would have the effect of hitting for 910 damage.  For 115 mana, thats insanely efficent.<P>On a lower level mob with say 5k hps, it would do around 450 ish, less useful but still efficent.  So when you got the spell it would be useful, and it would grow as you gained levels and attacked harder things.<P>In order to curb the usefulness of the spell, it shouldn't be able to land on any mob with more than 32k hps.<P>Also it is not like a dot, it can only be cast once, and then you have to use other spells to get the benifit, so you would only get the 9:1 ratio once per mob, limiting its exploitability.<P>I'm trying to think about it, and see how unbalanced this would be, and I think it would really help up the damage groups can do with a cleric, without actually improving clerics damage dealing capabilities substancially.<P>What do people think? <BR><p>[This message has been edited by Aldur (edited 05-02-2002).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kessina</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I think it is a matter of perspective.  You are right that MoK is pretty useless as a regen.  But I tend see MoK as a DS counter instead and it works wonderfully.  If I use MoK is DS situations, its efficiency goes up much higher since the tank is taking much less damage, I have to heal less, and I can med uninterrupted.<P>I look at MoR in similar manner.  It is fairly useless against blue mobs but for blood red boss mobs that hit fast and often, especially if they rampage, MoR is another layer that improve the fight.<P>I think MoK and MoR were intended to be used in specific situations, not as a general purpose regen or ds.  That's why they can't compete with those from other classes.  But when used correctly, no other class can do the equivalent.<P>Just my 2 cents.<P>------------------<BR>Kessina Terok - 56 Templar of Tunare - The Hand - Xev Server</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">menleniel2</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I've never found aggro from mor to be problem, seem rare that it get aggro. Using mor and mok in a single group in akheva ruins I rarely had to throw out a heal.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aldur</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The point was kessina, if you wanted to strip the damage shield component, any caster can do that just as well.  On stuff where you really do need to strip it, like certain drakes in tov, you can't land it regardless of debuffs.<P>At level 56, how many red mobs are you fighting for exp?  Even non uber raid mobs don't really benifit from mok, other than stripping the damage shield simply because damage is never distributed evenly, a few tanks will get hit and that is it, and it is almost guaranteed to give less hps back than regrowth of the grove, yet that has no resistance, and guaranteed results.<P>menleniel2 I think what you are mentioning is the effects of slow, not mok.  You slow a mob in akheva and you don't need to heal period.  <P>Mok is a placebo effect, you think it is doing something useful but its not.  And the same is true for mok on a reasonable amount of mobs.  Remember in many situations cleric spell slots are limited, having mor available for the odd critter is applicable for is far less useful than simply hitting them with judgement for more damage.<P>mor can have applicable situations at present, but they dwindle considerably as you gain in levels.  I still have not found a useful non ds stripping encounter where mok can be noticed it being on or off.<P>Look at it this way, I can either take 9 seconds of my time casting mok for limited effect (forgetting resists), or 12 seconds of my time for a guaranteed 105 group heal.  I think there is no dispute which is more useful.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">JanSorensen</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">MoK and MoR just scale badly as people get better gear.<P>Judgement - without or without focus items - is almost always a better choice than MoR for a number of reasons.<BR>- You dont have to cast it early in the fight (if you cast MoR way early you wont be sitting down right away).<BR>- You can "stack" several nukes on the same mob (while you cannot MoR the mob twice)<BR>- It simply does more dmg/time standing.<P>MoR has its uses, yes, but they are few and far between except for unslowable raid level mobs.<P>MoK I never mem - but sometimes I click my BP when bored if I cannot sit due to aggro anyway. More often I click my legs instead though.<P>This doesnt make these spells bad - they just loose their power as you level/gear up.<P>------------------<BR><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4264" TARGET=_blank>Mikar of the Nexus</A><BR>High Priest of Brell<BR><A HREF="http://companions.windsofstorm.net/" TARGET=_blank>The Companions</A><BR>The Tribunal</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aldur</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aye but the biggest gripe all casters have in the end game is scaleability of power.  Its just a shame that level 60 clerics have less options than lower level ones, especially when at level 60 is especially the time clerics need those options.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Jubal</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Lord Feshlak's skin gleams with a dull red aura  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P><BR>Yeah MoK is worthless in any situation except powerlevelling very low level characters.<P>MoR is actually pretty decent on ubermobs that can be MR debuffed... I think THO is the ideal place to use it, since melee damage sucks so bad its effect is magnified. On smaller scale mobs it sucks too though.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Thistleburr</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Greetings!<P>I use MoR primarily for soloing (dual-wielding guards in Sanctus Seru, for example). Damage Shield + free heals + free rune + channeling focus = dead mob!<P>------------------<BR><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.jsp?num=1922" TARGET=_blank><B>Thistleburr</B></A>, High Priestess of Bristlebane<BR><A HREF="http://www.evguild.org" TARGET=_blank><I>Elitists and Vagrants</I></A>, Tribunal Server</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Gryfalia</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Speaking of using MoK to remove damage<BR>shields