mer drakes are MAGIC IMMUNE.  Even with full debuffs, you will never, even partially land a magic based spell on them.<P>MOK:  MOK is used where fights will go long, and to help the other melees heal a bit since your concentrating on the MT.  Examples of this are ToV raids, Larger mobs in Keal, and other rare spawns that are serious undercons for thier level. Its also good to pop ONLY damage shields, as dispell takes off all buffs (including debuffs) while trying to get damage shields.<P>MOR: MOR is pretty awesome, when you can land it.  Obviously its not for EXP groups, as you should be sluaghtering the lowest level solid blue you can find, so as to get your kills per minute very high. <P>the value, and difficulty of both of these spells is simple.. we are NOT classes that do damage shields.  that we have them in any form is sort of a anomily.  I would rather see mages and druids getting these veriants than us.  But, since we do have them, they come with a price.  That price is quite high:  bad mana to effect ratio, difficulty landing the spell, and single target use. <P>The upsides are simple awesome:  they stack with all other forms of shielding, including each other!  Mobs that rampage and flurry, make MOR a breeze to pay for itself, even when the mob is extremely low on health, and MOK is a breeze any time you have more than two tanks attacking.  At level 56, i dont have judgement, so these spells pay for themselves much faster.  At 125 mana, and then im back to medding, MOK slows damage enough in my normal group (war, rog, mage pet) that i typicly only have to heal the tank, and even then im down to just CHing. (my rog and tank both have 18 delay primary hand items, and have haste items and haste on them)<P>These are both situational only spells. Properly used though, they are extremely powerful.  TOV-HOT is the perfect place, I have had MOR hit more than 60 times, and MOK over a raid that is getting AOEed is awesome.  assuming haste and everything else reduces the healing to only 3 per swing, thats an average of +8 healing per tick times the 20 melees present, you have 160 PER TICK regen coming off a 125 mana spell.<P>add to this that it makes us fairly good self contained powerlevelers, and they are really nice spells.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kessina</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sorry for the late reply Aldur, haven't been reading much lately.<P>I'll have to disagree with this:<P>"...if you wanted to strip the damage shield component, any caster can do that just as well..."<P>With all the tash, malo, or what not landed, no other class can strip DS and only DS, that's where MoK shines.  And that was my whole point on MoK.  Don't look at it as a heal or regen, look at it as a DS remover that does not cancel any other spells.  In that respect, MoK is unique.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Belhaven</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I use Marks quite a bit, usually in EXP (or small raid) situations when we don't have a shaman to Slow and chanter to Mez.<P>MoR on all incoming mobs that will live longer than 20 hits or so softens them up with TINY aggro attributed to me.  An offtank can keep them busy and then I can med.  <P>MoK is used primarly to wipe Damage Shields, but is also handy to help the offtank stay healthy until the rest get on it.  Defensive doesn't slow the attacker, so he's hitting as often, taking less damage and getting a small amount of healing while doing so.<P><p>[This message has been edited by Belhaven (edited 05-10-2002).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Cilene</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">MoK is a spell primarely used for pwrlvling, but always cast it on mobs, ive had a group in seb, with no war n no shaman, in group was bard ench cleric wiz n rogue with mor 